-- difference between store procedure and function

Parameter 	                                   Function	                                      Stored Procedure
Return Value  | Must return a single value using the RETURN keyword.	                     |     May or may not return values; uses OUT or IN OUT parameters to return zero or more values.
Usage in SQL  |Can be called directly within SQL statements (SELECT, WHERE, HAVING, etc.).|  Cannot be called directly within a SQL statement; must be executed using an EXECUTE or
              |                                                                                 |   CALL statement or from within a PL/SQL block.
DML Operations| Can contain DML statements, but this restricts their usage within SQL queries
              |    unless defined as an autonomous transaction.	                               | Commonly used for DML operations and transaction control (e.g., COMMIT, ROLLBACK).
Parameter Types|	Primarily uses IN parameters, although OUT or IN OUT parameters are 
               |   technically possible (but not recommended if calling from SQL).	              |Supports IN, OUT, and IN OUT parameters.
Calling from |
other Subprograms|	Can be called from a stored procedure.	                                     | Cannot be called directly from a function (except under specific advanced configurations 
                                                                                                |like autonomous transactions).

Error Handling|	Does not support TRY-CATCH (or EXCEPTION blocks for transaction management
               |   within a function called from SQL).	                                           | Supports EXCEPTION handling blocks and transaction management.
Purpose	     | Used for computations, calculations, or data transformations where a single
              |    result is needed.	                                                             | Used for executing business logic, managing data flow, and performing complex,
